<AbstractNarration>Proposal Number: DMS-0200756&lt;br/&gt;PI: Eric Weber&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;ABSTRACT&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;In the past twenty years, wavelet theory has developed&lt;br/&gt;into a fundamental area of mathematics and applied science.&lt;br/&gt;Intimately related are frame theory and sampling theory, all&lt;br/&gt;with a connection to harmonic analysis.   The proposed&lt;br/&gt;research will investigate group representations as  a &lt;br/&gt;unifying theme since they appear in the settings of wavelet,&lt;br/&gt;frame, and sampling theory.  The research of Weber will use&lt;br/&gt;existing tools from functional and harmonic analysis, while&lt;br/&gt;also developing tools related to group cocycles and maximal&lt;br/&gt;abelian self adjoint algebras as models of these objects.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;The proposed research is theoretical in nature, though much&lt;br/&gt;of it is motivated by problems in applied mathematics.  The&lt;br/&gt;goal of the research  of Weber is to establish a solid&lt;br/&gt;mathematical foundation of wavelet and frame theory. However,&lt;br/&gt;the research will potentially impact problems in applied&lt;br/&gt;mathematics and signal processing, such as digital signal &lt;br/&gt;multiplexing, redundant communications and secure&lt;br/&gt;communications.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
